1692<div>

1693<h2>

1694How to Choose the Right Outdoor Lighting</h2>

1695

1696

1697<p>

1698Outdoor lighting is a critical part of the functionality and curb appeal of your home. Not only do you need to be able to access pathways, porches, verandas, and patios after dark, but you want a home that looks appealing from the street. A well-lit house is a safe house. And here are the types of outdoor lights to consider:</p>

1699

1700

1701<ul>

1702

1703 <li>

1704Outdoor Wall Lighting</li>

1705

1706 <li>

1707Outdoor Ceiling Lighting</li>

1708

1709 <li>

1710Post Lighting</li>

1711

1712 <li>

1713Deck Lighting</li>

1714

1715 <li>

1716Outdoor Pathway Lighting</li>

1717

1718</ul>

1719

1720

1721<p>

1722Finding the right outdoor lights for your house takes a careful evaluation of the areas around your home and yard, but it also requires an eye towards aesthetics.</p>

1723

1724

1725<h2>

1726What are Outdoor Lights?</h2>

1727

1728

1729<p>

1730Obviously, the answer is in the name &ndash; lights made to handle whatever is outside. To learn if a light bulb or lighting fixture is made for the elements, look for the UL (Underwriters Laboratories) safety rating.</p>

1731

1732

1733<p>

1734A wet rating means it&rsquo;s designed to handle the elements, whether snow or rain. We recommend a wet rating when installing deck lighting, pathway lighting, pole lighting, and wall sconces not covered by an overhang.</p>

1735

1736

1737<p>

1738A damp rating means the light is designed only to handle moisture, fog, and high humidity. It won&rsquo;t hold up to constant rain, snow, or spray from a sprinkler. As such, a damp-rated light needs overhead protection, such as a patio, porch or gazebo. Outdoor lighting fixtures also have weather-ready finishes capable of handling great swings in temperature as well as moisture.</p>

1739

1740

1741<h2>

1742Illuminating the Types of Outdoor Lights</h2>

1743

1744

1745<p>

1746Every outdoor lighting fixture has a purpose, be it functional, decorative, or both. By understanding how these exterior light fixtures work within your outdoor spaces, you can achieve a functional and secure home with the type of aesthetic appeal designed to attract eyes from the roadway.</p>

1747

1748

1749<h3>

1750Outdoor Wall Lighting: Decorative &amp; Functional</h3>

1751

1752

1753<p>

1754Outdoor sconces are perhaps the most common type of outdoor lighting. Placed at entryways and along walls in areas where there is high foot traffic, <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-wall/">

1755<u>

1756outdoor wall lighting</u>

1757</a>

1758 is both practical and stylish. In addition to providing a clear view around your house, you can use them to emphasize architectural focal points, such as arch ways, brick and stone cladding, and more.</p>

1759

1760

1761<p>

1762Available in a variety of lighting angles and coverages, the direction of the wall light has a purpose. Down-lit outdoor sconces primarily highlight entrances and pathways near the home&rsquo;s architectural exterior. You can use down-lit lights for decorative purposes, but they are primarily functional.</p>

1763

1764

1765<p>

1766Up-lit sconces are primarily decorative. You can use these lighting fixtures to create a decorative wash of light and shadows to enhance your home&rsquo;s after-dark aesthetics. Some outdoor wall lights shine in both directions, creating a functional and decorative lighting design.</p>

1767

1768

1769<p>

1770Functionally, outdoor wall lighting applications contributes to safety and security. While most outdoor wall lights use bulbs between 100 to 400 lumens, security lighting designs typically use between 700 and 1400 lumens. This type of lighting blankets an entire area in a bright light, like driveways and backyard decks, leaving no shadows for burglars to hide.</p>

1771

1772

1773<h3>

1774Outdoor Ceiling Lights: Illuminating Patios &amp; Porches</h3>

1775

1776

1777<p>

1778While many homes rely on outdoor canned lights or recessed lights to fill out their <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-ceiling/">

1779<u>

1780outdoor ceiling lighting</u>

1781</a>

1782, thanks to their affordable functionality, there are a wide range of designs available. If you&rsquo;re looking for style, outdoor chandeliers and pendants are gaining in popularity and are excellent for adding some flare to your exterior. Sophisticated outdoor flush mounts are an excellent midrange option as well.</p>

1783

1784

1785<p>

1786For front porches, outdoor flush mounts are a popular choice because they boost curb appeal while remaining unobtrusive. However, chandeliers and pendants are great for high-ceiling porches. It&rsquo;s more common to use chandeliers and pendant lighting in back patio areas and verandas given the more personal setting compared to a front porch. And since these fixtures aren&rsquo;t seen from the roadway, you can get away with more austere or adventurous styles, as these types of lighting fixtures are aimed more towards ambient decorative lighting over functional lighting.</p>

1787

1788

1789<h3>

1790Post Lighting: The 360-Degree Yard &amp; Garden Lantern</h3>

1791

1792

1793<p>

1794Pole lights are personalized versions of street lights &ndash; heavy-duty, often cast-iron fixture attached to tall pole to illuminate a general area. Typically, you purchase the pole and the lighting fixture separately, though with the same finish. And most often, <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-post/">

1795<u>

1796post lighting</u>

1797</a>

1798 is installed in the front yard near where the driveway meets the walkway to the front door so that the lights large coverage area spans both areas, but post lights are also used to illuminate gardens and landscape.</p>

1799

1800

1801<p>

1802Most pole lights provide 360-degree coverage, which is why they often have between one and four light bulbs with lumens between 120 and 3500, depending on how much area you want illuminated. They also come in a variety of sizes and shapes, though most are based on a classic or rustic lantern style. On the smaller range, pole lights are the size of a standard hand-held lamp at 6&rdquo; x 12&rdquo;, but the large options are more than double this size.</p>

1803

1804

1805<h3>

1806Deck Lighting: Creating Ambience for Entertaining</h3>

1807

1808

1809<p>

1810If you enjoy backyard parties or relaxing outside after a long day, don&rsquo;t forget about <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-deck/">

1811<u>

1812deck lighting</u>

1813</a>

1814</p>

1815

1816

1817<p>

1818Since decks are typically made of wood or vinyl planks, creative deck lighting produces interesting shadows and contrasting washes, providing the ideal ambience for entertaining. Deck lights come in a variety of styles and sizes, ranging from the subtle, nearly invisible step lights to the bold carriage style post cap lights. You can use very dim lights with under 100 lumens or go for a bolder look by using 100 to 200 lumen bulbs on post cap lights to cover large outdoor areas.</p>

1819

1820

1821<h3>

1822Outdoor Pathway Lighting: Providing a Runway for Your Yard</h3>

1823

1824

1825<p>

1826With bulbs ranging between 12 and 100 lumens and close to the ground installation, pathway lighting combines a functional view of the path while also providing a decorative ambience. When used effectively, it can also create a more aesthetically appealing look to your front yard than pole lighting.</p>

1827

1828

1829<p>

1830<a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-pathway/">

1831<u>

1832Outdoor pathway lighting</u>

1833</a>

1834 is often the easiest and most affordable outdoor lights to install. The most popular pathway lights are either solar lights or battery powered. You simply stick the light into the ground near the path, allowing you to easily move and replace the lights as needed. And since these lights are not bright, the ambience along the path is often used to romantic affect.</p>

1835

1836

1837<h2>

1838How to Choose the Perfect Outdoor Lighting</h2>

1839

1840

1841<p>

1842There isn&rsquo;t a hard rule for choosing the perfect outdoor lighting. It requires careful evaluation and planning of your exterior spaces. As such, start by evaluating the functional needs of your outdoor spaces &ndash; what outdoor areas need lighting for safe accessibility and security. This helps you know where to put lights. Once you&rsquo;ve covered the functional aspects, turn your eye towards the creative &ndash; how can you enhance the after-dark image of your home and yard.</p>

1843

1844

1845<h3>

1846Start with a Purpose: Evaluate Your Exterior Spaces for Functional Lighting</h3>

1847

1848

1849<p>

1850Walk through your yard at night and assess every part of it, from the doors to the backyard corner, grading each area from accessibility and safety.</p>

1851

1852

1853<p>

1854To evaluate for accessibility, start with the areas of the highest foot traffic &ndash; driveways, steps, sidewalks, walkways, and side paths. Any area where someone walks needs to have lighting bright enough to provide safe footing. In addition, an outdoor wall sconce near where your garbage and recycling bins are stored is helpful for ensuring safe access when taking the trash out. Finally, consider adding an outdoor wall light or outdoor flush mount near every entrance to the house.</p>

1855

1856

1857<p>

1858From a safety standpoint, light is a deterrent. Thieves are less likely to enter a house through a well-lit entrance. While this includes sliding glass doors, garage doors, and the front door, it also includes windows. By placing lights strategically near ground-floor windows and easily accessible second floor windows, you create a home a thief likely passes by in favor of a darker one.</p>

1859

1860

1861<p>

1862For entrances, exterior light fixtures with a high lumen output and a bright white color temperature help create the clearest picture of the area. However, these lights are harsh when used too often, so consider placing softer lights near windows, using down-lighting at an angle that doesn&rsquo;t interfere with interior ambience.</p>

1863

1864

1865<p>

1866If you&rsquo;re not comfortable with your exterior being lit up after you turn down for the night, you can consider motion detector flood lights. These bright lights are designed to cover a large area and the motion detector only turns them on when needed. That said, motion detectors are often fickle, turning on when a cat strolls by or a branch shakes in the wind, so be careful with the sensitivity settings and the aim of the lights to minimize the light bleeding in through the windows.</p>

1867

1868

1869<h3>

1870Considering Energy Costs</h3>

1871

1872

1873<p>

1874If you&rsquo;re concerned with saving energy as you install outdoor lights, there are ways to increase energy efficiency and keep electric costs lower. Consider solar lights as a top option. Since they rely on solar energy, these lights don&rsquo;t require an electrician to tap into the electrical grid. And while solar lights are often expensive, the installation costs are relatively minor in comparison.</p>

1875

1876

1877<p>

1878You can also consider LED lights, which are 75% more energy efficient than a standard incandescent bulb. Similar to solar lights, LEDs have a higher up-front cost, but since these bulbs last longer and use less energy, they are more cost effective over time.</p>

1879

1880

1881<h3>

1882Highlight Curb Appeal</h3>

1883

1884

1885<p>

1886After evaluating your home for functional lighting, you can assess ways to improve the curb appeal. By considering the shape of the house, the curves and angles, and how the light and shadows play into it, you can create a home that&rsquo;s as pleasant to look at after dark as it is during the day.</p>

1887

1888

1889<p>

1890Consider ways to use up and down-lighting in interesting ways. Both create shadows while highlighting a specific area of the house. The contrast in light and dark makes the house more interesting to look at.</p>

1891

1892

1893<p>

1894Subtle outdoor wall lights accentuate the lines of your home. Landscape lights are excellent for creating backlighting for trees, knolls, and water features. In addition, using low-voltage pathway lights is excellent for creating a soft ambience for all the common walkways.</p>

1895

1896

1897<p>

1898In addition, consider the style of the fixture. You want to make sure the fixtures have a consistent style that matches the exterior of your home. For example, cast iron lamps are excellent if you&rsquo;re looking to achieve a farmhouse style.</p>

1899

1900

1901<p>

1902With some careful planning and consideration, you can achieve functional outdoor lighting that makes your home and yard stand out from the rest of the houses on your street.</p>

1903

1904

1905<h2>

1906Frequently Asked Questions About Outdoor Lighting</h2>

1907

1908

1909<p>

1910<strong>

1911Do you need special bulbs for outdoor lights?</strong>

1912</p>

1913

1914

1915<p>

1916Like the light fixture itself, the light bulb should have a UL listing for damp or wet areas. In most cases, the light bulbs package clearly shows that it&rsquo;s approved for outdoor use.</p>

1917

1918

1919<p>

1920<strong>

1921Are LED lights good for outdoor use?</strong>

1922</p>

1923

1924

1925<p>

1926Yes. LED lights are an excellent, energy-efficient option for outdoor lights. Not only can they create the same level of brightness achieved with incandescent bulbs, but the energy cost is way lower in the long run because they have a much longer life span and use much less electricity. That said, as with any light, you need to make sure it&rsquo;s received a UL rating approved for wet or damp areas.</p>

1927

1928

1929<p>

1930<strong>

1931What is the best material for outdoor lighting fixtures?</strong>

1932<br />

1933

1934Brass is the ideal material for outdoor lights, especially for coastal areas, because it holds up to even the harshest of environments. In addition, brass patinas very well. However, it&rsquo;s the most expensive material.</p>

1935

1936

1937<p>

1938Aluminum is affordable but doesn&rsquo;t handle the elements as well as most metals. Stainless Steel is a great mid-range material. It looks great and is protected from corrosion by a chromium oxide coating. However, it requires a lot of cleaning and maintenance to maintain its appearance.</p>

1939

1940

1941<p>

1942<strong>

1943How to choose the best sizes of outdoor lights?</strong>

1944<br />

1945

1946The size of the lighting products is largely determined by the type of outdoor lighting you want to achieve.</p>

1947

1948

1949<p>

1950For wall sconces and carriage lights, a fixture that is between 6&rdquo; and 12&rdquo; wide is ideal, especially when placed at least 6&rdquo; from a door frame.</p>

1951

1952

1953<p>

1954For chandeliers and pendants, a 12&rdquo; to 20&rdquo; light is the best option, depending on the height of the ceiling or overhang. Also, chandeliers installed over outdoor tables should be at least half as wide as the table.</p>

1955

1956

1957<p>

1958It&rsquo;s a good idea to make sure lamp posts lanterns are approximately a quarter the size of the post or pole.</p>

1959

1960

1961<p>

1962The best size for pathway lights varies according to how much area you want to illuminate.</p>

1963

1964

1965<p>

1966<strong>

1967How many lumens do you need for outdoor security lighting?</strong>

1968<br />

1969

1970With security lighting, you want to eliminate dim areas as much as possible. The minimum range for flood lighting applications is 700 lumens, but you can go much higher. With standard incandescent bulbs, the higher the wattage, the higher the lumens. As such, you can go with the maximum wattage as well.</p>

1971

1972

1973<p>

1974<strong>

1975Do LED lights attract bugs?</strong>

1976<br />

1977

1978It depends on the type of LED light bulb. Most insects are attracted to the visible UV and infrared light from the sun and moon because they use this to navigate. However, most insects don&rsquo;t see yellow light (around a 2700K color temperature). As such, some manufacturers make LED light bulbs and incandescent bulbs in this range called bug lights. Both types attract fewer bugs than lights with a broader color temperature.</p>

1979

1980

1981<p>

1982Some bugs are attracted to the heat of light sources. And this is where the LED bug light has an advantage over its incandescent cousin. Since energy efficient LED lights don&rsquo;t heat the surrounding area as much as incandescent bulbs, it attracts fewer bugs.</p>

1983

1984

1985<p>

1986<strong>

1987How much does it cost to install outdoor lighting?</strong>

1988<br />

1989

1990Most experts suggest planning for installation costs between $50 and $150, not including the light fixture. But this depends on many elements &ndash; the type of light, the location, how much prep work is required, and how much the average electrician charges in your geographical area.</p>

1991

1992

1993<p>

1994Installing a freestanding light post, for example, is often the most expensive because it&rsquo;s labor intensive, requiring underground pole supports and wiring. Alternatively, most pathway lights are cheap and easy to install because they don&rsquo;t require a professional and don&rsquo;t usually require tapping into the electrical grid system, requiring you to simply stick the light into the soil.</p>

1995

1996

1997<p>

1998<strong>

1999What is a good wattage for outdoor lights?</strong>

2000<br />

2001

2002For standard incandescent lights, anything under an 80-watt bulb is ideal, especially if you&rsquo;re concerned about energy use. However, since wattage directly correlates to brightness, consider the purpose of the light when looking at wattage. That said, modern outdoor LED light bulbs are far more energy efficient, allowing the same brightness while using far less energy.</p>

2003

2004

2005<h3>

2006Other Questions:</h3>

2007

2008

2009<p>

2010<strong>

2011What color temperature is best for outdoor lighting?</strong>

2012</p>

2013

2014

2015<p>

2016For most modern outdoor light sources, you want to stay in the 2500-4000K range, as this produces a warm, inviting light not unlike a fireplace.</p>

2017

2018

2019<p>

2020When lighting landscapes, like trees and bushes, a light in the 3000-4000K range is best because it allows the natural colors of the plants to shine through more effectively without being harsh. This range is often called moon lighting because it mimics the effects of moonlight.</p>

2021

2022

2023<p>

2024<strong>

2025What are the best outdoor floodlights?</strong>

2026</p>

2027

2028

2029<p>

2030Floodlights have the single purpose of covering a large area with a bright white light. You want to use flood lights with a very high lumen output, and fixtures with two lights on adjustable arms is even better to cover more ground.</p>

2031

2032

2033<p>

2034However, there are multiple types of floodlights and purposes. Whether you&rsquo;re lighting a sports court for night time tennis matches or blanketing a driveway to deter break ins, the best flood light depends on how you intend to use it. For security purposes, a dual-light fixture with motion detectors is an excellent option.</p>

2035

2036

2037<p>

2038Metal halide bulbs have been a popular bulb for sports court flood lights because of their brightness and high color temperature, making visibility excellent (which is why they are often used to light stadiums). But it&rsquo;s worth noting that metal halide bulbs take a long time to warm up and cool down, and they are prone to shatter from heat.</p>

2039

2040

2041<p>

2042<strong>

2043Do LED lights work in cold temperatures?</strong>

2044</p>

2045

2046

2047<p>

2048Yes, LEDs are made to work in the cold. They are less likely to break in lower temperatures and they don&rsquo;t lose energy efficiency. Since LEDs don&rsquo;t produce heat in the same manner as other light bulbs, the bulbs aren&rsquo;t subjected to extreme swings in temperature that cause standard incandescent bulbs to break and wear down.</p>

2049

2050

2051<p>

2052<strong>

2053What does &ldquo;dark sky rated&rdquo; mean?</strong>

2054</p>

2055

2056

2057<p>

2058A Dark Sky rated bulb means the light emits less blue light, leading to a reduction in light pollution &ndash; the reason stargazing is much better when you&rsquo;re camping in areas far away from cities and towns. Using Dark Sky rated lights in conjunction with strategic placement is the best way to minimize your homes impact on the overall light pollution as well as minimize light spillage onto other properties.</p>

2059

2060

2061<p>

2062<strong>

2063What are &ldquo;dusk to dawn&rdquo; lights?</strong>

2064</p>

2065

2066

2067<p>

2068These lights remove the hassle of remembering to flip a switch to turn on or turn off a light. Rather, they use a light sensor to automatically turn on at dusk and turn off at dawn.</p>

2069

2070

2071<h2>

2072Taking the Spotlight</h2>

2073

2074

2075<p>

2076Shining a light on your home and yard provides safety, security, and curb appeal. There&rsquo;s no reason why you can&rsquo;t have a home that shines like a jewel while deterring break-ins. We have a wide range of <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor/">

2077<u>

2078outdoor lights</u>

2079</a>

2080 to choose from. If you want help designing the right type of lighting for your outdoor spaces, check out our <a href="https://vevano.com/page/design-services/">

2081<u>

2082online room design</u>

2083</a>

2084 or consult with our designers&nbsp;at <a href="mailto:design@vevano.com">

2085<u>

2086design@vevano.com</u>

2087</a>

2088 or call us at 855-483-2629.</p>

animation"}},{"id":"d197832a-f585-4323-846f-58d82f8d2b01","type":"TEXTBLOCK","children":[],"richText":{"css":"","html":"\u003ch2\u003eHow to Choose the Right Outdoor Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOutdoor lighting is a critical part of the functionality and curb appeal of your home. Not only do you need to be able to access pathways, porches, verandas, and patios after dark, but you want a home that looks appealing from the street. A well-lit house is a safe house. And here are the types of outdoor lights to consider:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Wall Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Ceiling Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003ePost Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDeck Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Pathway Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFinding the right outdoor lights for your house takes a careful evaluation of the areas around your home and yard, but it also requires an eye towards aesthetics.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat are Outdoor Lights?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eObviously, the answer is in the name \u0026ndash; lights made to handle whatever is outside. To learn if a light bulb or lighting fixture is made for the elements, look for the UL (Underwriters Laboratories) safety rating.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA wet rating means it\u0026rsquo;s designed to handle the elements, whether snow or rain. We recommend a wet rating when installing deck lighting, pathway lighting, pole lighting, and wall sconces not covered by an overhang.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA damp rating means the light is designed only to handle moisture, fog, and high humidity. It won\u0026rsquo;t hold up to constant rain, snow, or spray from a sprinkler. As such, a damp-rated light needs overhead protection, such as a patio, porch or gazebo. Outdoor lighting fixtures also have weather-ready finishes capable of handling great swings in temperature as well as moisture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eIlluminating the Types of Outdoor Lights\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEvery outdoor lighting fixture has a purpose, be it functional, decorative, or both. By understanding how these exterior light fixtures work within your outdoor spaces, you can achieve a functional and secure home with the type of aesthetic appeal designed to attract eyes from the roadway.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Wall Lighting: Decorative \u0026amp; Functional\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOutdoor sconces are perhaps the most common type of outdoor lighting. Placed at entryways and along walls in areas where there is high foot traffic, \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-wall/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eoutdoor wall lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is both practical and stylish. In addition to providing a clear view around your house, you can use them to emphasize architectural focal points, such as arch ways, brick and stone cladding, and more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAvailable in a variety of lighting angles and coverages, the direction of the wall light has a purpose. Down-lit outdoor sconces primarily highlight entrances and pathways near the home\u0026rsquo;s architectural exterior. You can use down-lit lights for decorative purposes, but they are primarily functional.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUp-lit sconces are primarily decorative. You can use these lighting fixtures to create a decorative wash of light and shadows to enhance your home\u0026rsquo;s after-dark aesthetics. Some outdoor wall lights shine in both directions, creating a functional and decorative lighting design.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFunctionally, outdoor wall lighting applications contributes to safety and security. While most outdoor wall lights use bulbs between 100 to 400 lumens, security lighting designs typically use between 700 and 1400 lumens. This type of lighting blankets an entire area in a bright light, like driveways and backyard decks, leaving no shadows for burglars to hide.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Ceiling Lights: Illuminating Patios \u0026amp; Porches\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhile many homes rely on outdoor canned lights or recessed lights to fill out their \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-ceiling/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eoutdoor ceiling lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, thanks to their affordable functionality, there are a wide range of designs available. If you\u0026rsquo;re looking for style, outdoor chandeliers and pendants are gaining in popularity and are excellent for adding some flare to your exterior. Sophisticated outdoor flush mounts are an excellent midrange option as well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor front porches, outdoor flush mounts are a popular choice because they boost curb appeal while remaining unobtrusive. However, chandeliers and pendants are great for high-ceiling porches. It\u0026rsquo;s more common to use chandeliers and pendant lighting in back patio areas and verandas given the more personal setting compared to a front porch. And since these fixtures aren\u0026rsquo;t seen from the roadway, you can get away with more austere or adventurous styles, as these types of lighting fixtures are aimed more towards ambient decorative lighting over functional lighting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003ePost Lighting: The 360-Degree Yard \u0026amp; Garden Lantern\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePole lights are personalized versions of street lights \u0026ndash; heavy-duty, often cast-iron fixture attached to tall pole to illuminate a general area. Typically, you purchase the pole and the lighting fixture separately, though with the same finish. And most often, \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-post/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003epost lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is installed in the front yard near where the driveway meets the walkway to the front door so that the lights large coverage area spans both areas, but post lights are also used to illuminate gardens and landscape.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMost pole lights provide 360-degree coverage, which is why they often have between one and four light bulbs with lumens between 120 and 3500, depending on how much area you want illuminated. They also come in a variety of sizes and shapes, though most are based on a classic or rustic lantern style. On the smaller range, pole lights are the size of a standard hand-held lamp at 6\u0026rdquo; x 12\u0026rdquo;, but the large options are more than double this size.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eDeck Lighting: Creating Ambience for Entertaining\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you enjoy backyard parties or relaxing outside after a long day, don\u0026rsquo;t forget about \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-deck/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003edeck lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSince decks are typically made of wood or vinyl planks, creative deck lighting produces interesting shadows and contrasting washes, providing the ideal ambience for entertaining. Deck lights come in a variety of styles and sizes, ranging from the subtle, nearly invisible step lights to the bold carriage style post cap lights. You can use very dim lights with under 100 lumens or go for a bolder look by using 100 to 200 lumen bulbs on post cap lights to cover large outdoor areas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Pathway Lighting: Providing a Runway for Your Yard\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith bulbs ranging between 12 and 100 lumens and close to the ground installation, pathway lighting combines a functional view of the path while also providing a decorative ambience. When used effectively, it can also create a more aesthetically appealing look to your front yard than pole lighting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-pathway/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eOutdoor pathway lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is often the easiest and most affordable outdoor lights to install. The most popular pathway lights are either solar lights or battery powered. You simply stick the light into the ground near the path, allowing you to easily move and replace the lights as needed. And since these lights are not bright, the ambience along the path is often used to romantic affect.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eHow to Choose the Perfect Outdoor Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThere isn\u0026rsquo;t a hard rule for choosing the perfect outdoor lighting. It requires careful evaluation and planning of your exterior spaces. As such, start by evaluating the functional needs of your outdoor spaces \u0026ndash; what outdoor areas need lighting for safe accessibility and security. This helps you know where to put lights. Once you\u0026rsquo;ve covered the functional aspects, turn your eye towards the creative \u0026ndash; how can you enhance the after-dark image of your home and yard.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eStart with a Purpose: Evaluate Your Exterior Spaces for Functional Lighting\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWalk through your yard at night and assess every part of it, from the doors to the backyard corner, grading each area from accessibility and safety.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eTo evaluate for accessibility, start with the areas of the highest foot traffic \u0026ndash; driveways, steps, sidewalks, walkways, and side paths. Any area where someone walks needs to have lighting bright enough to provide safe footing. In addition, an outdoor wall sconce near where your garbage and recycling bins are stored is helpful for ensuring safe access when taking the trash out. Finally, consider adding an outdoor wall light or outdoor flush mount near every entrance to the house.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFrom a safety standpoint, light is a deterrent. Thieves are less likely to enter a house through a well-lit entrance. While this includes sliding glass doors, garage doors, and the front door, it also includes windows. By placing lights strategically near ground-floor windows and easily accessible second floor windows, you create a home a thief likely passes by in favor of a darker one.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor entrances, exterior light fixtures with a high lumen output and a bright white color temperature help create the clearest picture of the area. However, these lights are harsh when used too often, so consider placing softer lights near windows, using down-lighting at an angle that doesn\u0026rsquo;t interfere with interior ambience.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026rsquo;re not comfortable with your exterior being lit up after you turn down for the night, you can consider motion detector flood lights. These bright lights are designed to cover a large area and the motion detector only turns them on when needed. That said, motion detectors are often fickle, turning on when a cat strolls by or a branch shakes in the wind, so be careful with the sensitivity settings and the aim of the lights to minimize the light bleeding in through the windows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eConsidering Energy Costs\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026rsquo;re concerned with saving energy as you install outdoor lights, there are ways to increase energy efficiency and keep electric costs lower. Consider solar lights as a top option. Since they rely on solar energy, these lights don\u0026rsquo;t require an electrician to tap into the electrical grid. And while solar lights are often expensive, the installation costs are relatively minor in comparison.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYou can also consider LED lights, which are 75% more energy efficient than a standard incandescent bulb. Similar to solar lights, LEDs have a higher up-front cost, but since these bulbs last longer and use less energy, they are more cost effective over time.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eHighlight Curb Appeal\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAfter evaluating your home for functional lighting, you can assess ways to improve the curb appeal. By considering the shape of the house, the curves and angles, and how the light and shadows play into it, you can create a home that\u0026rsquo;s as pleasant to look at after dark as it is during the day.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eConsider ways to use up and down-lighting in interesting ways. Both create shadows while highlighting a specific area of the house. The contrast in light and dark makes the house more interesting to look at.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSubtle outdoor wall lights accentuate the lines of your home. Landscape lights are excellent for creating backlighting for trees, knolls, and water features. In addition, using low-voltage pathway lights is excellent for creating a soft ambience for all the common walkways.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIn addition, consider the style of the fixture. You want to make sure the fixtures have a consistent style that matches the exterior of your home. For example, cast iron lamps are excellent if you\u0026rsquo;re looking to achieve a farmhouse style.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith some careful planning and consideration, you can achieve functional outdoor lighting that makes your home and yard stand out from the rest of the houses on your street.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eFrequently Asked Questions About Outdoor Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo you need special bulbs for outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eLike the light fixture itself, the light bulb should have a UL listing for damp or wet areas. In most cases, the light bulbs package clearly shows that it\u0026rsquo;s approved for outdoor use.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAre LED lights good for outdoor use?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYes. LED lights are an excellent, energy-efficient option for outdoor lights. Not only can they create the same level of brightness achieved with incandescent bulbs, but the energy cost is way lower in the long run because they have a much longer life span and use much less electricity. That said, as with any light, you need to make sure it\u0026rsquo;s received a UL rating approved for wet or damp areas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is the best material for outdoor lighting fixtures?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nBrass is the ideal material for outdoor lights, especially for coastal areas, because it holds up to even the harshest of environments. In addition, brass patinas very well. However, it\u0026rsquo;s the most expensive material.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAluminum is affordable but doesn\u0026rsquo;t handle the elements as well as most metals. Stainless Steel is a great mid-range material. It looks great and is protected from corrosion by a chromium oxide coating. However, it requires a lot of cleaning and maintenance to maintain its appearance.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow to choose the best sizes of outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nThe size of the lighting products is largely determined by the type of outdoor lighting you want to achieve.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor wall sconces and carriage lights, a fixture that is between 6\u0026rdquo; and 12\u0026rdquo; wide is ideal, especially when placed at least 6\u0026rdquo; from a door frame.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor chandeliers and pendants, a 12\u0026rdquo; to 20\u0026rdquo; light is the best option, depending on the height of the ceiling or overhang. Also, chandeliers installed over outdoor tables should be at least half as wide as the table.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIt\u0026rsquo;s a good idea to make sure lamp posts lanterns are approximately a quarter the size of the post or pole.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe best size for pathway lights varies according to how much area you want to illuminate.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow many lumens do you need for outdoor security lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nWith security lighting, you want to eliminate dim areas as much as possible. The minimum range for flood lighting applications is 700 lumens, but you can go much higher. With standard incandescent bulbs, the higher the wattage, the higher the lumens. As such, you can go with the maximum wattage as well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo LED lights attract bugs?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nIt depends on the type of LED light bulb. Most insects are attracted to the visible UV and infrared light from the sun and moon because they use this to navigate. However, most insects don\u0026rsquo;t see yellow light (around a 2700K color temperature). As such, some manufacturers make LED light bulbs and incandescent bulbs in this range called bug lights. Both types attract fewer bugs than lights with a broader color temperature.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSome bugs are attracted to the heat of light sources. And this is where the LED bug light has an advantage over its incandescent cousin. Since energy efficient LED lights don\u0026rsquo;t heat the surrounding area as much as incandescent bulbs, it attracts fewer bugs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow much does it cost to install outdoor lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nMost experts suggest planning for installation costs between $50 and $150, not including the light fixture. But this depends on many elements \u0026ndash; the type of light, the location, how much prep work is required, and how much the average electrician charges in your geographical area.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eInstalling a freestanding light post, for example, is often the most expensive because it\u0026rsquo;s labor intensive, requiring underground pole supports and wiring. Alternatively, most pathway lights are cheap and easy to install because they don\u0026rsquo;t require a professional and don\u0026rsquo;t usually require tapping into the electrical grid system, requiring you to simply stick the light into the soil.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is a good wattage for outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nFor standard incandescent lights, anything under an 80-watt bulb is ideal, especially if you\u0026rsquo;re concerned about energy use. However, since wattage directly correlates to brightness, consider the purpose of the light when looking at wattage. That said, modern outdoor LED light bulbs are far more energy efficient, allowing the same brightness while using far less energy.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOther Questions:\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat color temperature is best for outdoor lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor most modern outdoor light sources, you want to stay in the 2500-4000K range, as this produces a warm, inviting light not unlike a fireplace.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhen lighting landscapes, like trees and bushes, a light in the 3000-4000K range is best because it allows the natural colors of the plants to shine through more effectively without being harsh. This range is often called moon lighting because it mimics the effects of moonlight.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat are the best outdoor floodlights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFloodlights have the single purpose of covering a large area with a bright white light. You want to use flood lights with a very high lumen output, and fixtures with two lights on adjustable arms is even better to cover more ground.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eHowever, there are multiple types of floodlights and purposes. Whether you\u0026rsquo;re lighting a sports court for night time tennis matches or blanketing a driveway to deter break ins, the best flood light depends on how you intend to use it. For security purposes, a dual-light fixture with motion detectors is an excellent option.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMetal halide bulbs have been a popular bulb for sports court flood lights because of their brightness and high color temperature, making visibility excellent (which is why they are often used to light stadiums). But it\u0026rsquo;s worth noting that metal halide bulbs take a long time to warm up and cool down, and they are prone to shatter from heat.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo LED lights work in cold temperatures?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYes, LEDs are made to work in the cold. They are less likely to break in lower temperatures and they don\u0026rsquo;t lose energy efficiency. Since LEDs don\u0026rsquo;t produce heat in the same manner as other light bulbs, the bulbs aren\u0026rsquo;t subjected to extreme swings in temperature that cause standard incandescent bulbs to break and wear down.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat does \u0026ldquo;dark sky rated\u0026rdquo; mean?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA Dark Sky rated bulb means the light emits less blue light, leading to a reduction in light pollution \u0026ndash; the reason stargazing is much better when you\u0026rsquo;re camping in areas far away from cities and towns. Using Dark Sky rated lights in conjunction with strategic placement is the best way to minimize your homes impact on the overall light pollution as well as minimize light spillage onto other properties.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat are \u0026ldquo;dusk to dawn\u0026rdquo; lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThese lights remove the hassle of remembering to flip a switch to turn on or turn off a light. Rather, they use a light sensor to automatically turn on at dusk and turn off at dawn.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eTaking the Spotlight\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eShining a light on your home and yard provides safety, security, and curb appeal. There\u0026rsquo;s no reason why you can\u0026rsquo;t have a home that shines like a jewel while deterring break-ins. Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOutdoor lighting is a critical part of the functionality and curb appeal of your home. Not only do you need to be able to access pathways, porches, verandas, and patios after dark, but you want a home that looks appealing from the street. A well-lit house is a safe house. And here are the types of outdoor lights to consider:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Wall Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Ceiling Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003ePost Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDeck Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eOutdoor Pathway Lighting\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFinding the right outdoor lights for your house takes a careful evaluation of the areas around your home and yard, but it also requires an eye towards aesthetics.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eWhat are Outdoor Lights?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eObviously, the answer is in the name \u0026ndash; lights made to handle whatever is outside. To learn if a light bulb or lighting fixture is made for the elements, look for the UL (Underwriters Laboratories) safety rating.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA wet rating means it\u0026rsquo;s designed to handle the elements, whether snow or rain. We recommend a wet rating when installing deck lighting, pathway lighting, pole lighting, and wall sconces not covered by an overhang.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA damp rating means the light is designed only to handle moisture, fog, and high humidity. It won\u0026rsquo;t hold up to constant rain, snow, or spray from a sprinkler. As such, a damp-rated light needs overhead protection, such as a patio, porch or gazebo. Outdoor lighting fixtures also have weather-ready finishes capable of handling great swings in temperature as well as moisture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eIlluminating the Types of Outdoor Lights\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEvery outdoor lighting fixture has a purpose, be it functional, decorative, or both. By understanding how these exterior light fixtures work within your outdoor spaces, you can achieve a functional and secure home with the type of aesthetic appeal designed to attract eyes from the roadway.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Wall Lighting: Decorative \u0026amp; Functional\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOutdoor sconces are perhaps the most common type of outdoor lighting. Placed at entryways and along walls in areas where there is high foot traffic, \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-wall/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eoutdoor wall lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is both practical and stylish. In addition to providing a clear view around your house, you can use them to emphasize architectural focal points, such as arch ways, brick and stone cladding, and more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAvailable in a variety of lighting angles and coverages, the direction of the wall light has a purpose. Down-lit outdoor sconces primarily highlight entrances and pathways near the home\u0026rsquo;s architectural exterior. You can use down-lit lights for decorative purposes, but they are primarily functional.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUp-lit sconces are primarily decorative. You can use these lighting fixtures to create a decorative wash of light and shadows to enhance your home\u0026rsquo;s after-dark aesthetics. Some outdoor wall lights shine in both directions, creating a functional and decorative lighting design.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFunctionally, outdoor wall lighting applications contributes to safety and security. While most outdoor wall lights use bulbs between 100 to 400 lumens, security lighting designs typically use between 700 and 1400 lumens. This type of lighting blankets an entire area in a bright light, like driveways and backyard decks, leaving no shadows for burglars to hide.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Ceiling Lights: Illuminating Patios \u0026amp; Porches\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhile many homes rely on outdoor canned lights or recessed lights to fill out their \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-ceiling/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eoutdoor ceiling lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, thanks to their affordable functionality, there are a wide range of designs available. If you\u0026rsquo;re looking for style, outdoor chandeliers and pendants are gaining in popularity and are excellent for adding some flare to your exterior. Sophisticated outdoor flush mounts are an excellent midrange option as well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor front porches, outdoor flush mounts are a popular choice because they boost curb appeal while remaining unobtrusive. However, chandeliers and pendants are great for high-ceiling porches. It\u0026rsquo;s more common to use chandeliers and pendant lighting in back patio areas and verandas given the more personal setting compared to a front porch. And since these fixtures aren\u0026rsquo;t seen from the roadway, you can get away with more austere or adventurous styles, as these types of lighting fixtures are aimed more towards ambient decorative lighting over functional lighting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003ePost Lighting: The 360-Degree Yard \u0026amp; Garden Lantern\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePole lights are personalized versions of street lights \u0026ndash; heavy-duty, often cast-iron fixture attached to tall pole to illuminate a general area. Typically, you purchase the pole and the lighting fixture separately, though with the same finish. And most often, \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-post/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003epost lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is installed in the front yard near where the driveway meets the walkway to the front door so that the lights large coverage area spans both areas, but post lights are also used to illuminate gardens and landscape.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMost pole lights provide 360-degree coverage, which is why they often have between one and four light bulbs with lumens between 120 and 3500, depending on how much area you want illuminated. They also come in a variety of sizes and shapes, though most are based on a classic or rustic lantern style. On the smaller range, pole lights are the size of a standard hand-held lamp at 6\u0026rdquo; x 12\u0026rdquo;, but the large options are more than double this size.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eDeck Lighting: Creating Ambience for Entertaining\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you enjoy backyard parties or relaxing outside after a long day, don\u0026rsquo;t forget about \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-deck/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003edeck lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSince decks are typically made of wood or vinyl planks, creative deck lighting produces interesting shadows and contrasting washes, providing the ideal ambience for entertaining. Deck lights come in a variety of styles and sizes, ranging from the subtle, nearly invisible step lights to the bold carriage style post cap lights. You can use very dim lights with under 100 lumens or go for a bolder look by using 100 to 200 lumen bulbs on post cap lights to cover large outdoor areas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOutdoor Pathway Lighting: Providing a Runway for Your Yard\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith bulbs ranging between 12 and 100 lumens and close to the ground installation, pathway lighting combines a functional view of the path while also providing a decorative ambience. When used effectively, it can also create a more aesthetically appealing look to your front yard than pole lighting.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/lighting-outdoor-pathway/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eOutdoor pathway lighting\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e is often the easiest and most affordable outdoor lights to install. The most popular pathway lights are either solar lights or battery powered. You simply stick the light into the ground near the path, allowing you to easily move and replace the lights as needed. And since these lights are not bright, the ambience along the path is often used to romantic affect.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eHow to Choose the Perfect Outdoor Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThere isn\u0026rsquo;t a hard rule for choosing the perfect outdoor lighting. It requires careful evaluation and planning of your exterior spaces. As such, start by evaluating the functional needs of your outdoor spaces \u0026ndash; what outdoor areas need lighting for safe accessibility and security. This helps you know where to put lights. Once you\u0026rsquo;ve covered the functional aspects, turn your eye towards the creative \u0026ndash; how can you enhance the after-dark image of your home and yard.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eStart with a Purpose: Evaluate Your Exterior Spaces for Functional Lighting\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWalk through your yard at night and assess every part of it, from the doors to the backyard corner, grading each area from accessibility and safety.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eTo evaluate for accessibility, start with the areas of the highest foot traffic \u0026ndash; driveways, steps, sidewalks, walkways, and side paths. Any area where someone walks needs to have lighting bright enough to provide safe footing. In addition, an outdoor wall sconce near where your garbage and recycling bins are stored is helpful for ensuring safe access when taking the trash out. Finally, consider adding an outdoor wall light or outdoor flush mount near every entrance to the house.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFrom a safety standpoint, light is a deterrent. Thieves are less likely to enter a house through a well-lit entrance. While this includes sliding glass doors, garage doors, and the front door, it also includes windows. By placing lights strategically near ground-floor windows and easily accessible second floor windows, you create a home a thief likely passes by in favor of a darker one.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor entrances, exterior light fixtures with a high lumen output and a bright white color temperature help create the clearest picture of the area. However, these lights are harsh when used too often, so consider placing softer lights near windows, using down-lighting at an angle that doesn\u0026rsquo;t interfere with interior ambience.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026rsquo;re not comfortable with your exterior being lit up after you turn down for the night, you can consider motion detector flood lights. These bright lights are designed to cover a large area and the motion detector only turns them on when needed. That said, motion detectors are often fickle, turning on when a cat strolls by or a branch shakes in the wind, so be careful with the sensitivity settings and the aim of the lights to minimize the light bleeding in through the windows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eConsidering Energy Costs\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026rsquo;re concerned with saving energy as you install outdoor lights, there are ways to increase energy efficiency and keep electric costs lower. Consider solar lights as a top option. Since they rely on solar energy, these lights don\u0026rsquo;t require an electrician to tap into the electrical grid. And while solar lights are often expensive, the installation costs are relatively minor in comparison.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYou can also consider LED lights, which are 75% more energy efficient than a standard incandescent bulb. Similar to solar lights, LEDs have a higher up-front cost, but since these bulbs last longer and use less energy, they are more cost effective over time.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eHighlight Curb Appeal\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAfter evaluating your home for functional lighting, you can assess ways to improve the curb appeal. By considering the shape of the house, the curves and angles, and how the light and shadows play into it, you can create a home that\u0026rsquo;s as pleasant to look at after dark as it is during the day.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eConsider ways to use up and down-lighting in interesting ways. Both create shadows while highlighting a specific area of the house. The contrast in light and dark makes the house more interesting to look at.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSubtle outdoor wall lights accentuate the lines of your home. Landscape lights are excellent for creating backlighting for trees, knolls, and water features. In addition, using low-voltage pathway lights is excellent for creating a soft ambience for all the common walkways.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIn addition, consider the style of the fixture. You want to make sure the fixtures have a consistent style that matches the exterior of your home. For example, cast iron lamps are excellent if you\u0026rsquo;re looking to achieve a farmhouse style.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith some careful planning and consideration, you can achieve functional outdoor lighting that makes your home and yard stand out from the rest of the houses on your street.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eFrequently Asked Questions About Outdoor Lighting\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo you need special bulbs for outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eLike the light fixture itself, the light bulb should have a UL listing for damp or wet areas. In most cases, the light bulbs package clearly shows that it\u0026rsquo;s approved for outdoor use.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAre LED lights good for outdoor use?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYes. LED lights are an excellent, energy-efficient option for outdoor lights. Not only can they create the same level of brightness achieved with incandescent bulbs, but the energy cost is way lower in the long run because they have a much longer life span and use much less electricity. That said, as with any light, you need to make sure it\u0026rsquo;s received a UL rating approved for wet or damp areas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is the best material for outdoor lighting fixtures?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nBrass is the ideal material for outdoor lights, especially for coastal areas, because it holds up to even the harshest of environments. In addition, brass patinas very well. However, it\u0026rsquo;s the most expensive material.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAluminum is affordable but doesn\u0026rsquo;t handle the elements as well as most metals. Stainless Steel is a great mid-range material. It looks great and is protected from corrosion by a chromium oxide coating. However, it requires a lot of cleaning and maintenance to maintain its appearance.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow to choose the best sizes of outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nThe size of the lighting products is largely determined by the type of outdoor lighting you want to achieve.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor wall sconces and carriage lights, a fixture that is between 6\u0026rdquo; and 12\u0026rdquo; wide is ideal, especially when placed at least 6\u0026rdquo; from a door frame.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor chandeliers and pendants, a 12\u0026rdquo; to 20\u0026rdquo; light is the best option, depending on the height of the ceiling or overhang. Also, chandeliers installed over outdoor tables should be at least half as wide as the table.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIt\u0026rsquo;s a good idea to make sure lamp posts lanterns are approximately a quarter the size of the post or pole.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe best size for pathway lights varies according to how much area you want to illuminate.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow many lumens do you need for outdoor security lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nWith security lighting, you want to eliminate dim areas as much as possible. The minimum range for flood lighting applications is 700 lumens, but you can go much higher. With standard incandescent bulbs, the higher the wattage, the higher the lumens. As such, you can go with the maximum wattage as well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo LED lights attract bugs?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nIt depends on the type of LED light bulb. Most insects are attracted to the visible UV and infrared light from the sun and moon because they use this to navigate. However, most insects don\u0026rsquo;t see yellow light (around a 2700K color temperature). As such, some manufacturers make LED light bulbs and incandescent bulbs in this range called bug lights. Both types attract fewer bugs than lights with a broader color temperature.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSome bugs are attracted to the heat of light sources. And this is where the LED bug light has an advantage over its incandescent cousin. Since energy efficient LED lights don\u0026rsquo;t heat the surrounding area as much as incandescent bulbs, it attracts fewer bugs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHow much does it cost to install outdoor lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nMost experts suggest planning for installation costs between $50 and $150, not including the light fixture. But this depends on many elements \u0026ndash; the type of light, the location, how much prep work is required, and how much the average electrician charges in your geographical area.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eInstalling a freestanding light post, for example, is often the most expensive because it\u0026rsquo;s labor intensive, requiring underground pole supports and wiring. Alternatively, most pathway lights are cheap and easy to install because they don\u0026rsquo;t require a professional and don\u0026rsquo;t usually require tapping into the electrical grid system, requiring you to simply stick the light into the soil.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat is a good wattage for outdoor lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nFor standard incandescent lights, anything under an 80-watt bulb is ideal, especially if you\u0026rsquo;re concerned about energy use. However, since wattage directly correlates to brightness, consider the purpose of the light when looking at wattage. That said, modern outdoor LED light bulbs are far more energy efficient, allowing the same brightness while using far less energy.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eOther Questions:\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat color temperature is best for outdoor lighting?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor most modern outdoor light sources, you want to stay in the 2500-4000K range, as this produces a warm, inviting light not unlike a fireplace.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhen lighting landscapes, like trees and bushes, a light in the 3000-4000K range is best because it allows the natural colors of the plants to shine through more effectively without being harsh. This range is often called moon lighting because it mimics the effects of moonlight.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat are the best outdoor floodlights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFloodlights have the single purpose of covering a large area with a bright white light. You want to use flood lights with a very high lumen output, and fixtures with two lights on adjustable arms is even better to cover more ground.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eHowever, there are multiple types of floodlights and purposes. Whether you\u0026rsquo;re lighting a sports court for night time tennis matches or blanketing a driveway to deter break ins, the best flood light depends on how you intend to use it. For security purposes, a dual-light fixture with motion detectors is an excellent option.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMetal halide bulbs have been a popular bulb for sports court flood lights because of their brightness and high color temperature, making visibility excellent (which is why they are often used to light stadiums). But it\u0026rsquo;s worth noting that metal halide bulbs take a long time to warm up and cool down, and they are prone to shatter from heat.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDo LED lights work in cold temperatures?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYes, LEDs are made to work in the cold. They are less likely to break in lower temperatures and they don\u0026rsquo;t lose energy efficiency. Since LEDs don\u0026rsquo;t produce heat in the same manner as other light bulbs, the bulbs aren\u0026rsquo;t subjected to extreme swings in temperature that cause standard incandescent bulbs to break and wear down.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat does \u0026ldquo;dark sky rated\u0026rdquo; mean?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA Dark Sky rated bulb means the light emits less blue light, leading to a reduction in light pollution \u0026ndash; the reason stargazing is much better when you\u0026rsquo;re camping in areas far away from cities and towns. Using Dark Sky rated lights in conjunction with strategic placement is the best way to minimize your homes impact on the overall light pollution as well as minimize light spillage onto other properties.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat are \u0026ldquo;dusk to dawn\u0026rdquo; lights?\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThese lights remove the hassle of remembering to flip a switch to turn on or turn off a light. Rather, they use a light sensor to automatically turn on at dusk and turn off at dawn.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003eTaking the Spotlight\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eShining a light on your home and yard provides safety, security, and curb appeal. There\u0026rsquo;s no reason why you can\u0026rsquo;t have a home that shines like a jewel while deterring break-ins.
